In addition, a processing step is used to remove drift by calculating the
 offset required to zero measurements obtained outside cloud.
 This is done by adjusting the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 by nudging toward the value required to give zero liquid water content
 outside cloud (as indicated by another instrument, often a CDP showing
 droplet concentration of <1 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-3}$
\end_inset

).
 Specifically, when out-of-cloud, Nu
\begin_inset Formula $^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is calculated from Nu
\begin_inset Formula $^{\prime}=\mathrm{\{PLWC\}}/(\pi L\lambda_{c}(T_{s}-T_{a}))$
\end_inset

.
 Then the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 is updated via 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 += (Nu
\begin_inset Formula $^{\prime}/Re^{a_{1}}-a_{0})/\tau$
\end_inset

 (using, for the GV, separate coefficients for each of the three branches).
 In this formula, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 should be the number of updates in a fixed period, e.g., for a 100 s time
 constant and for 25-Hz processing, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=100\times25$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, to avoid jumps when switching among the branches, the linear
 coefficients {
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

} are adjusted with each transition between branches to provide a continuous
 estimate of the zero value.
